  "response": "Yes, the Indian government has officially acknowledged conducting surgical strikes across the Line of Control (LoC) in Pakistan-administered Kashmir on September 29, 2016. These strikes were in response to a terrorist attack on an Indian army base in Uri, Jammu and Kashmir, on September 18, 2016, which resulted in the deaths of 19 Indian soldiers. India attributed the Uri attack to Jaish-e-Mohammed, a Pakistan-based militant group.\n\nThe Indian military stated that the surgical strikes targeted terrorist launch pads and inflicted significant casualties on militants planning to infiltrate into Indian-administered Kashmir. The operation was carried out by the Indian Army's Special Forces, who crossed the LoC and struck multiple locations before returning to Indian territory.\n\nPakistan, however, denied that any surgical strikes took place and described the incident as cross-border firing. Despite Pakistan's denial, the Indian government and military have stood by their claims, and the operation was widely reported in Indian media and discussed in political debates.\n\nThe surgical strikes were seen as a significant shift in India's approach to counterterrorism and cross-border incidents, marking a more assertive stance in dealing with terrorist threats emanating from Pakistan.",
